Instance internals: Nitro, tenancy, and placement.

Under every modern instance sits the Nitro System, AWS's platform that offloads virtualization work, the networking, storage, and security, from the host C-P-U onto dedicated Nitro cards, and runs a stripped-down hypervisor on the host. The payoff is near bare-metal performance, because most of the host's C-P-U and R-A-M go to your instance. You also get hardware E-B-S encryption at no C-P-U cost, network ceilings up to a hundred to two hundred gigabits, and a hard security boundary where AWS operators have no path into your guest memory. Nitro also enables bare-metal instances, the dot-metal sizes, with no hypervisor at all. Those are rarely needed, except for running a nested hypervisor, socket-based licensing, or measuring raw hardware behaviour.

Tenancy controls how much hardware you share. Shared tenancy, the default, puts you on hardware with other customers, isolated at the hypervisor level. It's the cheapest, and it's the right choice almost always. A Dedicated Instance reserves hardware for your account. A Dedicated Host goes further and gives you a specific physical server with visible sockets; that's the one to pick when a licence is tied to physical sockets, or an audit needs host-level visibility.

Placement groups override AWS's default spreading. Cluster packs instances physically close for low-latency H-P-C. Spread puts each on distinct hardware for maximum resilience. And partition groups them into fault-isolated racks. Finally, the stop, hibernate, and terminate trio differ on state. Stop keeps the E-B-S root volume but loses R-A-M. Hibernate saves R-A-M to the encrypted root volume, so a slow-to-warm service resumes instantly. And terminate deletes the instance and, by default, its root volume.
